// Database Architecture

// Database architecture means that how the database is structured and how it works. It includes the design of the database, the way data is stored, and how it is accessed and managed. 

// Types of Database Architecture:

// 1. One-tier architecture: In this architecture, the database is directly accessed by the user. It is simple and easy to use but it is not suitable for large applications.
// 2. Two-tier architecture: In this architecture, the database is accessed through a client-server model. The client sends requests to the server, which processes the requests and returns the results. It is more efficient than one-tier architecture and is suitable for small to medium-sized applications.
// 3. Three-tier architecture: In this architecture, there is an additional layer called the application layer between the client and the server. The application layer handles the business logic and processes the requests from the client before sending them to the server. It is more scalable and flexible than two-tier architecture and is suitable for large applications.

